<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-03-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-03-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="1310" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1310">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.115/69.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Miller</persName> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Tampico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-03-04">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 4, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Department’s March 2. Consular Agent, Tuxpam, notified of instruction and
                            requested to present protest to jefe politico. General Zaragoza,
                            military commander and Governor at Tampico, assures me that Government
                            does not wish to assess forced loans on foreigners.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Miller</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>